Notes by the Way
-From-
Feb. 2nd to Oct. 28th
-1881-
E.A. Barnes
Chicago-Ill.

Notes by the Way
Continued.
-1881-
Feb. 2-
Father found this pretty blank book the other day. Someone is no doubt regretting its loss; while I am the gainer, for, having no use for the book himself, father gives it to me. He does not know how much I think of it, as his gift. I am going to put it to a certain use -- a continuation of my "notes." Could I have done better?
"""
The last Winter month is here -- a

short one, too.  I am not sorry; for I
long for spring again.
Good Sleighing
Feb. 3 -- 

 Yes, I resume my "notes" again;

& I have a nice book in which
to continue them.  Perhaps this book
came into my hands for this very purpose;
perhaps the Lord had something
to do with it, knowing how much
I would prize such a book.  A little
matter, I know, in which to implicate
the Lord; & yet not beneath His notice.
A week from to-night, Della expects
to take part in a Concert, to be hale at the
"little Church around the Corner."
Last year, my work of writing & revising

amounted to forty pieces.  Not many, I
know, in the course of a whole year -- still
they cost me much mental labor.
"Sleigh Bells"
Feb. 5 --
Uncle Josiah has gone to his
rest.  He died on the 30th of last
month.  He death leaves our dear mother
the only surviving member of her
father's family.  I think there is
something very sad in such an 
instanse.
"Faith's Record" comes to-day.  It
contains my poem -- The Christian.
I prize my "Records" more than ever,
since they make such a pretty book
when bound.
I have commenced to read & study

the 7th chapter of St Luke.  What
faith did the centurion have in Jesus!
And how promptly did that faith receive
its own reward!
Feb. 7 --
At present I am taking Library
books from a Mission Sunday School
near by.  I enjoy the privilege; but I do
not know how long it will last
Della has left "Covington's?."  She has
been at home over a month now -- just
where she ought to be, I think.
I think a great deal of my last Song
book -- "Gates of Praise."  Besides being
a pretty book, it contains three of my
best pieces -- one of which is my first 
Missionary hymn.  The other two are
favorites with me.  In my dreamy
moments, it does not take much to

Rhyme:
Drinks is a bitter unclear,
The wide world 'oer;
Unclear unclear [[unclear], oh! unclear, to-night,
And drink no more.
Feb. 12 --
I wish my dear father was not afflicted as he is -- physically, I mean. He has about him, & has had for years, a certain trouble, which, at times, is considered very dangerous, to say nothing of the pain that it gives him. Not many men would do as he does every day: & suffer pains at the same time. I pity him: but I can do can? nothing but pray for him.
Della? claims this book when I get to the last page. The dear girl is welcome to it: but she will have to wait a good long while, I am thinking.
